Developing a SOCIO-ECO-MRIO SFC Macroeconomic Model for the Philippines

Author

Oriol Vallès Codina

Published

March 11, 2025

Introduction

The Philippines faces significant economic challenges a decade before the 100th anniversary of its independence from the US in 2046. Despite the country’s commendable economic performance in recent years, persistent high poverty, social and regional inequality, unemployment and underemployment, fragile sustained growth, technological value-chain upgrading, and regional and global economic integration remain as key issues for the emerging economy (Aldaba, 2009; Llanto et al., 2015; Navarro & Almaden, 2018; Quimba et al., 2020), as mounting exposure to the climate crisis and the question of the sustainable energy transition in the context of a circular economy loom (Enerlan, 2023). To navigate these complexities, a nuanced and robust macroeconomic modeling framework that may yield policy insights is essential.

This research proposal aims to develop a stock-flow consistent (SFC) macroeconomic model with an input-output industrial structure, augmented by ecological and social extensions (in short, a SOCIO-ECO-MRIO SFC model following Bimpizas-Pinis et al. (2024) for a 54-sector EU-RoW framework), to showcase its modeling power and provide insightful policy guidance for the Philippines. While the model focused on circular-economy strategies in the Global North, our research showed the negative impacts that many of them can have on the Global South in terms of economic growth, employment, or financial stability. Hence, this research aims at understanding better how the economies of the Global South can prepare for such scenarios in the pressing context of the climate crisis.

Objectives and Timeline

  1. Develop a stylized core-periphery SFC model with a flexible exchange rate where the periphery includes assets such as agrarian land, mineral extraction, and remittances as a flow. Fall 2024
  2. Empirically calibrate for the Philippines and the Rest of the World (RoW) to reflect the economic realities and institutional structures, including skill differences and gender inequality. Early Spring 2025
  3. Simulate specific policy scenarios for technological value-chain upgrading in the context of sustainable development Late Spring 2025
  4. Produce two policy briefs based on the models developed, offering actionable recommendations for policy-makers. Summer 2025
  5. Create a publishable-quality research paper detailing the model’s development, calibration, and policy implications. Fall 2025
  6. Present the findings at the Angelo King Institute (AKI) through presentations or a computational workshop. Spring 2024, Fall 2025

Literature Review and Methodology

Stock-flow consistent models offer a comprehensive framework for analyzing economic dynamics, ensuring that all stocks and flows are accounted for in a coherent manner (Caverzasi & Godin, 2015; Godley & Lavoie, 2006; Nikiforos & Zezza, 2017). These models are complex dynamical systems of mainly discrete-time difference equations that provide a systematic framework for the dynamical analysis of the complex institutional structure of whole socio-economic systems, using 1) careful, rigorous double-accounting of the stocks and flows through extended social accounting and flow-of-funds matrices 2) sets of behavioral equations (Caverzasi & Godin, 2015; Nikiforos & Zezza, 2017).

The main contribution of early SFC models was their consistent and comprehensive integration of the flows and the stocks for both the real and the financial sides of the economy, which allowed them, unlike conventional macroeconomic models, to successfully anticipate both the 2008 Global Financial Crisis and the 2010-12 Eurozone sovereign debt crisis (Godley, 2012b, 2012a; Godley & Lavoie, 2006). In the pressing context of the climate crisis, a SFC analysis is particularly well-suited to capture the complex dynamic interactions between the environment and the economy (Dafermos et al., 2017, 2018; Jackson & Victor, 2020). Unlike conventional macroeconomic models, SFC models belong to the broader family of system dynamics, of widespread use in the natural sciences and engineering.

Within the broad field of ecological macroeconomics, the integration of environmentally-extended input-output (EE-IO) analysis with stock-flow consistent (SFC) modeling is one of the most promising methods for the simulation, evaluation, and comparison of sustainable strategies and their social outcomes due to its formal treatment of system dynamics, the complex institutional structure of the economy, and the distribution of income (Hardt & O’Neill, 2017). The current and most important challenge of ecological SFC models is the formal treatment of the open economy at the industry level, which would allow a sector-specific understanding of within-country and cross-country economy-environment interactions to better inform government policy at mitigating and adapting to climate change (Berg et al., 2015; Carnevali et al., 2020). At this moment, most ECO-SFC models still aggregate the economy into one or very few sectors, in particular the energy sector (Canelli et al., 2024; Carnevali et al., 2020; Naqvi, 2014; Valdecantos & Valentini, 2017). ECO-SFC models focus on climate and energy transition risks (Dunz et al., 2021; Magacho et al., 2023; Monasterolo & Raberto, 2018), emissions modeling in an SFC macro setting (Naqvi & Stockhammer, 2018; Valdecantos & Valentini, 2017), and the dynamic interactions between the economy and the environment (Canelli et al., 2024), while often only considering aggregate output and thus overlooking the vertical interdependencies between different industries (Carnevali et al., 2020; Dafermos et al., 2017). This also precludes the dynamical analysis of technological upgrading along the value chain, with the exception of Naqvi (2014). Finally, Valdecantos & Mazier (2015) and Valdecantos & Zezza (2015) analyzed potential reforms of the European and global financial monetary system in a multi-regional context, albeit without an industrial structure.

In short, the proposed approach is particularly suited for:

  • Capturing Complex Institutional Interactions empirically informed by input-output databases and national accounts, SFC models can capture the system-wide interactions between the environment and the economy, including as well as the financial sector, households, and firms, providing a holistic view of economic dynamics.

  • Policy Analysis These models are powerful tools for dynamic multi-dimensional policy analysis, enabling the simulation of various policy scenarios and their potential impacts on the economy.

  • Incorporating Social and Ecological Dimensions By integrating social dimensions such as inequalities in gender, class and labor skills, as well as the ecological impact of economic activity empirically informed by environmentally-extended input-output databases such as EXIOBASE (Stadler et al., 2018) or EORA (Lenzen et al., 2013).

In particular, the project aims to re-purpose the data-driven SOCIO-ECO-MRIO SFC macroeconomic model of Passarella et al (Bimpizas-Pinis et al., 2024), which included a multi-regional input-output economic structure with 54 industries as well as social and ecological extensions developed for the EU Horizon 2020 JUST2CE project on a socially just transition to a circular economy. In that case, the model was empirically calibrated to simulate a world economy with two regions, the EU and Rest of the World, with a focus on circular-economy interventions in the Global North such as reducing consumption, closing supply chain loops, more selective government spending, or extending product lifetimes. A main insight from the project are the intricate dynamical interactions between the environment and the core-periphery structure of the world economy, in which the low-income economies of the Global South are drained of financial, labor and environmental resources in favor of the richer economies of the Global North, while the Global South is to suffer the brunt of the climate crisis (Dorninger et al., 2021; Hickel et al., 2022). In this global context, our research showed that sustainability strategies exclusively focused on the Global North may seriously threaten economic growth, employment, and financial stability in the Global South, positing the urgent need for the sustainable development for low- and middle-income economies, especially if compensating policies from the Global North such as the cancellation of Global South public debt are not implemented.

In particular, this research aims at developing the model empirically calibrated for the Philippines and the Rest of the World with special attention at stylized facts of developing economies: assets such as agrarian land and minerals, the flow of remittances, unemployment and underemployment, and dynamics of technological value-chain upgrading. How could the rich natural assets of developing economies be employed towards upgrading their value chain? An important challenge of the development of the model is introducing a flexible exchange rate, which forces the adoption of more complex solver methods than the standard Gauss-Seidel approach (namely, the Broyden solver). Such complication explains why many complex SFC models do not address a flexible exchange rate – a specially critical issue for developing economies.

Expected Outcomes

  • a SOCIO-ECO-MRIO SFC model that explores strategies for sustainable development in the periphery instead of the core, in this case the Philippines
  • a working paper of publishable quality detailing the development, empirical calibration, and main findings of such a model
  • one or two presentations and/or a computational workshop

Scenario Example from the JUST2CE Project: Product Lifetime Extension

The JUST2CE SOCIO-ECO-MRIO SFC model simulates the world economy with two regions, Europe and the Rest of the World, and 54 industries (Section 6). The network of the input-output structure can be visualized, where the size of the nodes corresponds to the industry output and the alpha transparency of the links corresponds to the size of the input-output flow:

quartz_off_screen 
                2

which shows, for instance, the systemic relevance of Retail & Wholesale trade (40), Transportation (42), and Knowledge intensive business services (KIBS, 43), as well as Manufacturing of Durable Goods (28), and the important link between the extraction of fossil fuels (5) in the South and their processing (16) in the North.

Shocked Variables

A specific policy scenario of product lifetime extension in the context of the transition to a circular economy is implemented in a complex way: public investment increases in an on-off way, exclusively focused on research and development, for ten time periods following the policy shock and both the depreciation rate of fixed capital and the share of household consumption in manufacturing goods linearly decrease with a lag.

Ecological, Social and Economic Impacts

Macroeconomic, external, social, price, employment, inequality, and ecological indicators showing the complex impact of such a policy intervention can be analyzed with respect to the baseline: while in the long run all ecological indicators improve with the important exception of carbon emissions, gross output decreases, but real value added increases; consumption increases while employment decreases in both regions; the government deficit becomes a surplus at the expense of a deterioration in the external position of the Rest of the World; and the EU wage share of income declines, potentially exacerbating social inequality.

Summary Table

The table below shows the percentage change over the baseline for a myriad of model variables. The existence of win-lose scenarios in the context of the transition to a circular economy emphasizes the need for developing economies to focus on directing structural change towards ecological and economic sustainability as well as financial stability. Well-meaning sustainability strategies in the Global North may seriously threaten economic growth and employment in the Global South, while the latter suffers the brunt of climate change.
